# MANDATORY: GitFlow Workflow

Follow the [Atlassian GitFlow workflow](https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/comparing-workflows/gitflow-workflow).

## Branch roles (this repo)

| GitFlow branch | This repo | Purpose |
|----------------|-----------|---------|
| `main` | `master` | Production release history; tag shipped versions here |
| `develop` | `develop` | Integration branch for in-progress features |
| `feature/*` | `feature/*` or `feat/*` | Short-lived feature work |
| `release/*` | `release/*` | Release prep (bug fixes/docs only) |
| `hotfix/*` | `hotfix/*` | Urgent production patches |

## Rules

1. **Do not land feature work directly on `master`.** Branch from `develop`, merge back to `develop`.
2. **Features** start from latest `develop`:
   ```bash
   git checkout develop && git pull
   git checkout -b feature/my-change   # or feat/my-change
   ```
3. **Finish features** via PR into `develop` (not `master`).
4. **Releases** fork from `develop` as `release/x.y.z`. When ready, merge to
   `master` (tag version) and back to `develop`; delete `release/*` locally and
   on `origin` (see `gitflow-release-cleanup.mdc`).
5. **Hotfixes** fork from `master` only. When done, merge to both `master` and
   `develop`; delete `hotfix/*` locally and on `origin`.
6. **Never** let `feature/*` merge directly to `master`.
7. Use PRs for all merges into `develop` and `master`; keep branches short-lived.

## Agent checklist before push

- Confirm current branch type matches the work (feature vs hotfix vs release).
- Confirm merge target is correct (`develop` for features, `master` only for release/hotfix completion).
- Rebase or merge latest `develop` into long-lived feature branches before opening PR.

## Transition note

If `develop` is missing, create it from `master` once and use it for all new feature branches:

```bash
git checkout master && git pull
git checkout -b develop && git push -u origin develop
```
